WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:01.360 --> 00:00:04.002
Prof: So,
what I want to do today is

00:00:04.002 --> 00:00:08.029
resist the temptation to talk
about anarchism the entire time.

00:00:08.029 --> 00:00:13.131
I sent around the terms for
today of which I only forgot one

00:00:13.131 --> 00:00:13.910
or two.
 

00:00:13.910 --> 00:00:17.297
What I think I'll do at the
beginning is I'm going to talk

00:00:17.297 --> 00:00:20.886
very quickly about socialism,
and the difference between

00:00:20.886 --> 00:00:23.870
revolutionary socialism and
reform socialism.

00:00:23.870 --> 00:00:26.555
Add syndicalism to the mix,
and these are all terms that I

00:00:26.555 --> 00:00:29.193
sent to you, so I'm not going to
write them on the board,

00:00:29.193 --> 00:00:30.560
because I need the board.
 

00:00:30.560 --> 00:00:32.656
Then for most of the lecture
I'm going to talk about

00:00:32.656 --> 00:00:33.150
anarchism.
 

00:00:33.150 --> 00:00:36.850
Anarchists didn't want to
reform the state.

00:00:36.850 --> 00:00:40.598
They didn't want to seize
control of the state either by

00:00:40.598 --> 00:00:43.120
revolution or by electoral
process.

00:00:43.120 --> 00:00:46.110
They wanted to destroy the
state.

00:00:46.110 --> 00:00:49.870
So, I'm going to talk about
those guys for a while.

00:00:49.870 --> 00:00:52.020
Most anarchists were not
terrorists,

00:00:52.020 --> 00:00:55.902
but at the end I'm going to
talk about a guy that I followed

00:00:55.902 --> 00:00:59.390
around for four or five years
who was a terrorist,

00:00:59.390 --> 00:01:02.409
and arguably--it's a book I
just finished--one can find the

00:01:02.409 --> 00:01:04.650
origins of modern terrorism in
this guy,

00:01:04.650 --> 00:01:08.879
who is called Émile
Henry.

00:01:08.879 --> 00:01:11.000
This will fit into Paris.
 

00:01:11.000 --> 00:01:13.659
It's obviously sort of a
sub-theme in this course,

00:01:13.659 --> 00:01:15.670
and so is the state and
capitalism.

00:01:15.670 --> 00:01:19.962
This particular person,
Émile Henry,

00:01:19.962 --> 00:01:23.030
set out to bomb and to kill.
 

00:01:23.030 --> 00:01:28.299
His targets changed the name of
the game for terrorists.

00:01:28.299 --> 00:01:32.739
That's obviously what I can't
wait to talk about.

00:01:32.739 --> 00:01:35.709
But first I'm going to just
review briefly for you,

00:01:35.709 --> 00:01:38.170
it's getting briefer every
second that I think about this,

00:01:38.170 --> 00:01:40.580
the socialist stuff,
which you can read about.

00:01:44.830 --> 00:01:50.536
With the rise of mass politics
in Europe in the 1880s and

00:01:50.536 --> 00:01:56.040
1890s, there was the rise of
mass socialist parties.

00:01:56.040 --> 00:01:59.974
Basically just to review:
there are two kinds of

00:01:59.974 --> 00:02:00.980
socialism.
 

00:02:00.980 --> 00:02:03.650
There were the revolutionary
socialists,

00:02:03.650 --> 00:02:10.597
of which Marx was an obvious
example and his son-in-law Paul

00:02:10.597 --> 00:02:12.903
Lafargue,
a name you don't have to

00:02:12.903 --> 00:02:15.514
retain,
who brought Marxist theory to

00:02:15.514 --> 00:02:18.544
France,
who believed that revolution

00:02:18.544 --> 00:02:23.693
would come when the proletariat
was class-conscious and after a

00:02:23.693 --> 00:02:27.555
bourgeois revolution,
of which he basically thought

00:02:27.555 --> 00:02:30.508
1848 had been a good example
following in 1789.

00:02:30.508 --> 00:02:35.478
And the proletariat would rise
up and break their chains and

00:02:35.478 --> 00:02:37.919
bring this brave new world.
 

00:02:37.919 --> 00:02:41.742
And, so, there were
revolutionary socialists in

00:02:41.742 --> 00:02:44.235
Italy, in Spain,
and in France,

00:02:44.235 --> 00:02:46.729
and even a few in Germany.
 

00:02:46.729 --> 00:02:52.471
Reform socialists said,
"Look, states are becoming

00:02:52.471 --> 00:02:58.000
stronger and stronger,
and can break revolutions very

00:02:58.000 --> 00:02:59.169
easily.
 

00:02:59.169 --> 00:03:03.221
Look what happened to the Paris
Commune of 1871 when about

00:03:03.221 --> 00:03:05.780
25,000 people are massacred,
men,

00:03:05.780 --> 00:03:07.908
women and children are gunned
down,

00:03:07.908 --> 00:03:13.028
and that the way to bringing
social reform and abolishing the

00:03:13.028 --> 00:03:17.038
abuses of capitalism is through
reform."

00:03:17.038 --> 00:03:21.000
This is the reformist tradition
in Germany.

00:03:21.000 --> 00:03:24.107
It's identified with somebody
who's in the book,

00:03:24.107 --> 00:03:25.430
Edouard Bernstein.
 

00:03:25.430 --> 00:03:28.810
And you can see this in the
growth of the SPD,

00:03:28.810 --> 00:03:32.878
the German Socialist Reformist
Party,

00:03:32.878 --> 00:03:39.422
which was the largest party in
the Reichstag in 1914 when war

00:03:39.422 --> 00:03:40.840
breaks out.
 

00:03:40.840 --> 00:03:46.169
What you do is if you organize,
you can--legislatures,

00:03:46.169 --> 00:03:51.119
if you have enough socialists
and enough well-meaning other

00:03:51.119 --> 00:03:54.940
people in the legislatures,
in the Reichstag,

00:03:54.940 --> 00:03:56.400
or in the Chambre des
Députés,

00:03:56.400 --> 00:03:59.229
or the other parliaments in
places that had parliaments,

00:03:59.229 --> 00:04:01.080
then you can vote in laws.
 

00:04:01.080 --> 00:04:05.540
You can vote in mine safety
regulations, because mining

00:04:05.540 --> 00:04:08.348
accidents killed so many people.
 

00:04:08.348 --> 00:04:10.907
There's one in the Pas de
Calais where hundreds and

00:04:10.907 --> 00:04:13.465
hundreds of people,
a thousand people get killed in

00:04:13.465 --> 00:04:15.460
one accident in about 1910 or
1911.

00:04:15.460 --> 00:04:20.579
You can pass an eight-hour day
or a ten-hour day.

00:04:20.579 --> 00:04:23.879
You can pass laws making it
harder and harder to employ

00:04:23.879 --> 00:04:26.569
children, particularly in
dangerous tasks.

00:04:26.569 --> 00:04:30.259
You can do things for women.
 

00:04:30.259 --> 00:04:31.790
You could do things for
families.

00:04:31.790 --> 00:04:35.471
If you elect the right kind of
people, you can have a

00:04:35.471 --> 00:04:38.870
revolution through reform,
through the ballot.

00:04:38.870 --> 00:04:41.709
And the great socialist leaders
such as Bernstein,

00:04:41.709 --> 00:04:43.836
whom I just mentioned,
or the great Jean

00:04:43.836 --> 00:04:47.564
Jaurès,
whose death on the 31^(st) of

00:04:47.564 --> 00:04:53.589
July in 1914 was really the end
of an era and the beginning of

00:04:53.589 --> 00:04:57.966
another era,
a scary era of the war--people

00:04:57.966 --> 00:04:59.459
had that sense.
 

00:04:59.459 --> 00:05:04.762
He was the one who in France
unified the reform socialists

00:05:04.762 --> 00:05:09.321
and the revolutionary
socialists, though there are

00:05:09.321 --> 00:05:12.949
still fissures in their
approaches.

00:05:12.949 --> 00:05:15.732
Of course, the old
revolutionary socialists would

00:05:15.732 --> 00:05:17.819
become the Communists after
1920,

00:05:17.819 --> 00:05:21.524
when the French Communist Party
is begun in the wake of the

00:05:21.524 --> 00:05:23.730
Russian Revolution,
which seemed to be,

00:05:23.730 --> 00:05:28.550
even though it was a revolution
in a very complex situation,

00:05:28.550 --> 00:05:31.230
that seemed to say that you can
have a revolution.

00:05:31.230 --> 00:05:36.110
But anyway, reform socialists
dominate in Germany.

00:05:36.110 --> 00:05:37.779
They dominate in France.
 

00:05:37.779 --> 00:05:38.920
They dominate in Belgium.
 

00:05:38.920 --> 00:05:41.970
The Socialist Party is terribly
important in Italy;

00:05:41.970 --> 00:05:44.569
they become more important in
Spain as well.

00:05:44.569 --> 00:05:48.800
Those are the two big
traditions.

00:05:48.800 --> 00:05:52.166
Some of the tensions between
revolutionary socialists and

00:05:52.166 --> 00:05:55.714
reform socialists can be seen in
the fact that revolutionary

00:05:55.714 --> 00:05:57.699
socialists said,
"Look,

00:05:57.699 --> 00:06:01.685
if you are working in the
Reichstag and you're trying to

00:06:01.685 --> 00:06:05.307
get better insurance
plans," ironically it was

00:06:05.307 --> 00:06:09.437
Bismarck's Germany that gives
really the first substantial

00:06:09.437 --> 00:06:13.341
insurance program for workers,
"what you're doing is

00:06:13.341 --> 00:06:15.220
you're propping up the bourgeois
state.

00:06:15.220 --> 00:06:16.459
You're buying into it.
 

00:06:16.459 --> 00:06:20.362
You're supporting indirectly
their armies that crush workers

00:06:20.362 --> 00:06:23.536
and strikes,"
and they did in the heroic age

00:06:23.536 --> 00:06:25.718
of syndicalism,
but more about that in a

00:06:25.718 --> 00:06:29.339
minute,
1895 to about 1907 in France.

00:06:29.339 --> 00:06:30.980
But in other countries it's
about the same thing.

00:06:30.980 --> 00:06:34.779
"You're propping up the
bourgeois state by participating

00:06:34.779 --> 00:06:36.680
in electoral politics."
 

00:06:36.680 --> 00:06:38.870
But lots of revolutionary
socialists,

00:06:38.870 --> 00:06:41.300
and this is all in the book so
don't worry about this,

00:06:41.300 --> 00:06:43.160
but a lot of them say,
"Look,

00:06:43.160 --> 00:06:44.930
if we don't run candidates and
elections,

00:06:44.930 --> 00:06:46.569
how are they going to know
about us?"

00:06:46.569 --> 00:06:48.894
So, they, too,
would run candidates and

00:06:48.894 --> 00:06:49.629
elections.
 

00:06:49.629 --> 00:06:51.639
So, they're put at really kind
of coincé.

00:06:51.639 --> 00:06:54.151
They're really sort of stuck
between a rock and a hard place,

00:06:54.151 --> 00:06:56.454
because they're running
candidates in elections in which

00:06:56.454 --> 00:06:57.459
they do not believe.
 

00:07:01.069 --> 00:07:02.389
I'm not here talking about
Russia,

00:07:02.389 --> 00:07:04.230
because that is more
complicated with the Bolsheviks,

00:07:04.230 --> 00:07:05.918
and the Mensheviks,
and the socialist

00:07:05.918 --> 00:07:08.100
revolutionaries,
and we will come back to them.

00:07:08.100 --> 00:07:11.970
I'm talking basically about
Western Europe.

00:07:11.970 --> 00:07:16.369
You have to imagine that Lenin
and the other Russian socialists

00:07:16.369 --> 00:07:20.767
are sort of walking around the
lakes of Geneva and of Zurich in

00:07:20.767 --> 00:07:23.889
exile and trying to imagine this
future.

00:07:23.889 --> 00:07:27.153
But that's the big difference
between socialists,

00:07:27.153 --> 00:07:28.990
reform and revolutionary.
 

00:07:28.990 --> 00:07:32.394
Now, to make things even more
complicated, you have a group

00:07:32.394 --> 00:07:33.920
called the syndicalists.
 

00:07:33.920 --> 00:07:36.002
The word
"syndicalist"

00:07:36.002 --> 00:07:39.968
is an English word which I sent
along on your friendly email

00:07:39.968 --> 00:07:41.379
from yours truly.
 

00:07:41.379 --> 00:07:44.339
Syndicalist,
the word comes from the French

00:07:44.339 --> 00:07:47.579
word for unions,
which is a syndicat.

00:07:47.579 --> 00:07:50.350
What they said is,
"Hang on."

00:07:50.350 --> 00:07:52.675
They kind of believed with the
revolutionary socialists,

00:07:52.675 --> 00:07:54.452
saying,
"If you get involved in

00:07:54.452 --> 00:07:56.639
electoral process,
you are propping up this

00:07:56.639 --> 00:07:57.910
corrupt bourgeois state.
 

00:07:57.910 --> 00:08:01.673
You are propping up this
dynamic duo of the state and

00:08:01.673 --> 00:08:03.050
capitalism."
 

00:08:03.050 --> 00:08:06.629
Syndicalists say,
"Look, we will organize

00:08:06.629 --> 00:08:10.367
from the ground up,
beginning in the shop floor,

00:08:10.367 --> 00:08:11.639
the factory.
 

00:08:11.639 --> 00:08:15.860
That will be not only a means
to obtain a revolution,

00:08:15.860 --> 00:08:19.773
it's a way of seeing what the
future world will be like when

00:08:19.773 --> 00:08:22.625
everybody tutoies
everybody or Dus

00:08:22.625 --> 00:08:23.819
everybody.
 

00:08:23.819 --> 00:08:28.654
The kind of relations,
the friendly equal relations of

00:08:28.654 --> 00:08:32.240
the shop floor become,
after the revolution,

00:08:32.240 --> 00:08:34.850
the way the world will be
organized."

00:08:34.850 --> 00:08:37.634
In the South of Europe,
in Italy and in Spain,

00:08:37.634 --> 00:08:40.913
these folks are called,
and I sent this around to you,

00:08:40.913 --> 00:08:42.460
anarcho-syndicalists.
 

00:08:42.460 --> 00:08:44.080
You see a transition here.
 

00:08:44.080 --> 00:08:45.850
Anarcho-syndicalists.
 

00:08:45.850 --> 00:08:50.429
Because they're rejecting the
state and they're looking in the

00:08:50.429 --> 00:08:54.558
future, the decentralized
organization is part of it.

00:08:54.558 --> 00:08:59.600
Anarcho-syndicalists have
considerable influence in Spain

00:08:59.600 --> 00:09:00.678
and Italy.
 

00:09:00.678 --> 00:09:03.576
They believe in direct action,
and sabotage,

00:09:03.576 --> 00:09:06.340
and strikes,
but in union organization.

00:09:06.340 --> 00:09:11.177
One of the most interesting--I
mention him in the book--Fernand

00:09:11.177 --> 00:09:12.269
Pelloutier,
 

00:09:18.129 --> 00:09:20.090
who wrote a book called The
Dying Society,

00:09:20.090 --> 00:09:23.179
was one of the theoreticians of
anarcho-syndicalism,

00:09:23.179 --> 00:09:24.409
of syndicalism.
 

00:09:24.409 --> 00:09:26.139
He was dying.
 

00:09:26.139 --> 00:09:27.940
He was dying of TB.
 

00:09:27.940 --> 00:09:30.307
Though he was not a worker,
tuberculosis was a

00:09:30.307 --> 00:09:31.570
working-class disease.
 

00:09:31.570 --> 00:09:32.820
Go to Pennsylvania.
 

00:09:32.820 --> 00:09:34.308
Go to West Virginia.
 

00:09:34.308 --> 00:09:36.772
Tuberculosis,
the ravages of the mines in the

00:09:36.772 --> 00:09:38.899
United States,
were just incredible.

00:09:38.899 --> 00:09:42.585
In porcelain factories and all
sorts of places,

00:09:42.585 --> 00:09:45.548
glass factories all over the
place.

00:09:45.548 --> 00:09:48.840
Pelloutier creates these things
called labor exchanges.

00:09:48.840 --> 00:09:52.404
He's one of the people who come
to these things called labor

00:09:52.404 --> 00:09:55.269
exchanges,
bourse de travail,

00:09:55.269 --> 00:10:00.032
you call them in French,
which were towns where you had

00:10:00.032 --> 00:10:04.556
municipal socialists in power at
the municipal level--and you

00:10:04.556 --> 00:10:06.330
did,
in some cities,

00:10:06.330 --> 00:10:09.869
are giving municipal funds to
start these labor exchanges

00:10:09.869 --> 00:10:11.259
which are buildings.
 

00:10:11.259 --> 00:10:12.649
You can still see them.
 

00:10:12.649 --> 00:10:15.865
When I was invited to Limoges
to give a big talk by the

00:10:15.865 --> 00:10:18.485
Conféderation
Général du

00:10:18.485 --> 00:10:19.995
Travail,
we started the

00:10:19.995 --> 00:10:22.528
apéro,
the first round of drinks,

00:10:22.528 --> 00:10:24.779
about noon in the labor
exchange,

00:10:24.779 --> 00:10:27.259
in the maison du peuple,
the house of the people.

00:10:27.259 --> 00:10:30.201
They were places where workers
coming from other places could

00:10:30.201 --> 00:10:32.113
come and get a meal,
get some money and,

00:10:32.113 --> 00:10:33.830
above all, find out about jobs.
 

00:10:33.830 --> 00:10:37.230
So, syndicalists--the way they
imagine the future,

00:10:37.230 --> 00:10:41.250
and preparing for this brave
new world of post-revolutionary

00:10:41.250 --> 00:10:43.683
relationships,
that has an important

00:10:43.683 --> 00:10:46.658
privileged place in the way they
view the world.

00:10:46.658 --> 00:10:49.799
There was an engineer called
Georges Sorel,

00:10:49.799 --> 00:10:53.538
whose name I should have send
around, S-O-R-E-L.

00:10:53.538 --> 00:10:57.610
He comes to the notion of the
general strike.

00:10:57.610 --> 00:11:01.177
One day all workers will simply
put down their tools and say,

00:11:01.177 --> 00:11:03.200
"Hell with you,
capitalism.

00:11:03.200 --> 00:11:05.399
Hell with you, the State.
 

00:11:05.399 --> 00:11:08.639
And they will bring capitalism
to its knees."

00:11:08.639 --> 00:11:11.450
It doesn't really ever work out
that way, does it?

00:11:11.450 --> 00:11:15.110
The capitalists and the State
win the day.

00:11:15.110 --> 00:11:19.410
So, having rushed through all
of that, let me talk about what

00:11:19.410 --> 00:11:21.058
I want to talk about.
 

00:11:21.058 --> 00:11:23.812
That is anarchism,
of which there is only a couple

00:11:23.812 --> 00:11:26.845
short, and I hope sprightly,
paragraphs in which you're

00:11:26.845 --> 00:11:27.519
reading.
 

00:11:27.519 --> 00:11:29.370
I am not an anarchist.
 

00:11:29.370 --> 00:11:33.658
Sometimes when I give talks at
various places--I was at St.

00:11:33.658 --> 00:11:36.110
Louis recently,
and other places,

00:11:36.110 --> 00:11:37.769
people at the end will
think--hopefully,

00:11:37.769 --> 00:11:38.840
they'll never think I'm a
terrorist,

00:11:38.840 --> 00:11:41.898
because I'm certainly not,
and when I talk about this guy

00:11:41.898 --> 00:11:44.668
I do not do so with affection or
admiration.

00:11:44.668 --> 00:11:46.860
But I know him because I
followed him around.

00:11:46.860 --> 00:11:48.769
I followed him around.
 

00:11:48.769 --> 00:11:53.830
Most anarchists were not
terrorists.

00:11:53.830 --> 00:11:55.990
One wants to make that clear.
 

00:11:55.990 --> 00:12:01.551
It's not surprising that the
great strengths of anarchism are

00:12:01.551 --> 00:12:07.019
in Spain in Catalonia and in
Andalusia in the south of Spain

00:12:07.019 --> 00:12:09.429
and in southern Italy.
 

00:12:09.429 --> 00:12:10.830
Why?
 

00:12:10.830 --> 00:12:14.332
Because that's where the
Italian and the Spanish states

00:12:14.332 --> 00:12:18.096
have very limited success in
convincing people that they're

00:12:18.096 --> 00:12:19.590
Spanish or Italian.
 

00:12:19.590 --> 00:12:21.830
Why should they believe they're
Spanish or Italian?

00:12:21.830 --> 00:12:25.879
Southern Italians thought that
the republic was a monarchy.

00:12:25.879 --> 00:12:29.206
But the progressive monarchy,
so called, was a plot launched

00:12:29.206 --> 00:12:32.534
by tax collectors and industrial
capitalists in the North of

00:12:32.534 --> 00:12:33.100
Italy.
 

00:12:33.100 --> 00:12:38.500
In Andalusia and in Catalonia
were the Civil Guard,

00:12:38.500 --> 00:12:42.399
who tended to be from Galicia,
a conservative part of Spain

00:12:42.399 --> 00:12:46.149
where the odious Franco was from
or from Castile,

00:12:46.149 --> 00:12:49.658
a huge area around Madrid.
 

00:12:49.658 --> 00:12:52.265
It was easy to see how they
associated the state with

00:12:52.265 --> 00:12:53.970
something that they didn't want.
 

00:12:53.970 --> 00:12:58.452
In writing about anarchism,
I tried to put myself and tried

00:12:58.452 --> 00:13:02.009
to think of how anarchists
viewed the world.

00:13:02.009 --> 00:13:05.149
I want to tell you a story
that's a true story.

00:13:05.149 --> 00:13:10.009
If you're trying to imagine how
anarchists viewed the world,

00:13:10.009 --> 00:13:12.480
this story is not a bad one.
 

00:13:12.480 --> 00:13:18.861
It's about a cork worker making
corks for bottles of sherry in

00:13:18.861 --> 00:13:21.059
the south of Spain.
 

00:13:21.059 --> 00:13:23.070
He's dying.
 

00:13:23.070 --> 00:13:25.519
He'd been an anarchist his
entire life.

00:13:25.519 --> 00:13:27.500
He hated the state.
 

00:13:27.500 --> 00:13:30.289
He hated capitalism.
 

00:13:30.289 --> 00:13:32.139
He hated the church.
 

00:13:32.139 --> 00:13:34.600
He's dying.
 

00:13:34.600 --> 00:13:36.320
He's on his deathbed.
 

00:13:36.320 --> 00:13:41.815
He had married a woman from a
religiously practicing Catholic

00:13:41.815 --> 00:13:42.639
family.
 

00:13:42.639 --> 00:13:48.450
In the scene in this room in
which he's dying,

00:13:48.450 --> 00:13:51.740
in one part of the room is his
family,

00:13:51.740 --> 00:13:55.812
who hated organized religion,
who view it as a prop for

00:13:55.812 --> 00:13:57.690
capitalism and the state.
 

00:13:57.690 --> 00:14:01.049
On the other side of the room
are people who are not so sure.

00:14:01.049 --> 00:14:03.230
They went to church sometimes.
 

00:14:03.230 --> 00:14:04.500
They knew the priest.
 

00:14:04.500 --> 00:14:09.538
When he's lying there,
the end is near.

00:14:09.538 --> 00:14:13.370
His wife's family says,
"Pedro,

00:14:13.370 --> 00:14:17.860
don't you want me to bring a
lawyer in?

00:14:17.860 --> 00:14:23.129
A lawyer who will take your
last will."

00:14:23.129 --> 00:14:26.581
Anarchists don't have wills and
they don't have very much

00:14:26.581 --> 00:14:27.259
property.
 

00:14:27.259 --> 00:14:30.726
The other side of the room is
just utter terror,

00:14:30.726 --> 00:14:31.389
horror.
 

00:14:31.389 --> 00:14:34.764
How can they suggest such a
thing, that Pedro is going to

00:14:34.764 --> 00:14:35.610
make a will?
 

00:14:35.610 --> 00:14:38.048
That's a bourgeois thing to do,
to make a will.

00:14:38.048 --> 00:14:41.794
Then somebody else from his
wife's family says,

00:14:41.794 --> 00:14:44.320
"Pedro,
the end is near.

00:14:44.320 --> 00:14:48.038
Don't you want us to get a
priest for the last

00:14:48.038 --> 00:14:49.279
rights?"
 

00:14:49.279 --> 00:14:54.269
He'd never set foot in a church
and proudly so.

00:14:54.269 --> 00:14:56.840
Consternation on the other side
of the room.

00:14:56.840 --> 00:14:59.129
How will it all end?
 

00:14:59.129 --> 00:15:00.960
How will Pedro end his life?
 

00:15:00.960 --> 00:15:03.120
With a lawyer and a priest?
 

00:15:03.120 --> 00:15:08.190
So, Pedro looks up and he says,
"Go and get me a lawyer.

00:15:08.190 --> 00:15:09.558
Bring me a lawyer."
 

00:15:09.558 --> 00:15:13.985
Then he says,
"Go and tell father,"

00:15:13.985 --> 00:15:18.409
the priest, "to come to
see me."

00:15:18.409 --> 00:15:22.928
Joy--utter consternation.
 

00:15:22.928 --> 00:15:25.620
Pedro's lying in a bed in the
middle.

00:15:25.620 --> 00:15:29.692
So, pretty soon the lawyer
comes dressed in his little

00:15:29.692 --> 00:15:30.230
suit.
 

00:15:30.230 --> 00:15:33.940
He doesn't yet have a
calculator to tote up the bill,

00:15:33.940 --> 00:15:36.009
but he's got his legal pad.
 

00:15:36.009 --> 00:15:38.908
He's never been in that house
before.

00:15:38.908 --> 00:15:43.200
He comes down by the bed and he
says, "Pedro,

00:15:43.200 --> 00:15:46.966
you have a few possessions,
a fork, a knife,

00:15:46.966 --> 00:15:48.980
a couple of plates.
 

00:15:48.980 --> 00:15:51.710
Don't you want to give me your
will now?"

00:15:51.710 --> 00:15:54.490
Pedro says, "Wait a minute.
 

00:15:54.490 --> 00:15:56.230
Wait a minute,
señor.

00:15:56.230 --> 00:15:57.779
Wait a minute."
 

00:15:57.779 --> 00:15:59.470
Then the priest comes.
 

00:15:59.470 --> 00:16:05.174
He has his purple--I remember
this from Jesuit high school

00:16:05.174 --> 00:16:09.080
days--thing that they wear on
Easter.

00:16:09.080 --> 00:16:14.135
He has his little case also,
which he has the holy oil to

00:16:14.135 --> 00:16:18.019
bless Pedro and give him the
last rights.

00:16:18.019 --> 00:16:21.523
He comes close and he says,
"Pedro,

00:16:21.523 --> 00:16:23.139
the end is near.
 

00:16:23.139 --> 00:16:27.062
You've led a good life,
but I haven't seen you in

00:16:27.062 --> 00:16:30.659
church very much or ever,
for that matter.

00:16:30.659 --> 00:16:32.649
Your children are not baptized.
 

00:16:32.649 --> 00:16:35.690
Don't you want to make a
confession?

00:16:35.690 --> 00:16:38.000
You're going to meet your maker
soon.

00:16:38.000 --> 00:16:41.309
Don't you want to make a
confession to me right now?

00:16:41.309 --> 00:16:42.870
Nobody can hear you.
 

00:16:42.870 --> 00:16:47.548
Don't you have something you
want to tell me?

00:16:47.548 --> 00:16:54.009
Isn't there something you can
tell me?"

00:16:54.009 --> 00:17:00.070
Consternation on one side,
silent joy on the other.

00:17:00.070 --> 00:17:02.940
Pedro says to the lawyer,
"Come here,

00:17:02.940 --> 00:17:04.480
señor.
 

00:17:04.480 --> 00:17:07.588
I want you to stand on the left
side of my bed."

00:17:07.588 --> 00:17:10.933
He says to the priest,
"Father,

00:17:10.933 --> 00:17:12.750
come here please.
 

00:17:12.750 --> 00:17:17.818
I want you to stand on the
right side of my bed."

00:17:17.818 --> 00:17:22.818
Then he smiles a smile of utter
contempt.

00:17:22.818 --> 00:17:27.269
He says, "Now you can all
see both sides of the family.

00:17:27.269 --> 00:17:30.534
Like Christ,
I am dying between two

00:17:30.534 --> 00:17:32.069
thieves."
 

00:17:32.069 --> 00:17:33.930
And he died.
 

00:17:33.930 --> 00:17:40.386
To imagine the kind of hate
that anarchists had of soldiers,

00:17:40.386 --> 00:17:44.000
and priests,
and of officials,

00:17:44.000 --> 00:17:49.920
and of Castilian Guardia Civil,
that was how anarchism was born.

00:17:49.920 --> 00:17:52.160
When was anarchism born?
 

00:17:52.160 --> 00:17:54.423
There's a couple antecedents in
the eighteenth century,

00:17:54.423 --> 00:17:57.025
but they're terribly irrelevant
people that hardly anyone read,

00:17:57.025 --> 00:17:58.200
including a British one.
 

00:17:58.200 --> 00:18:02.730
It really starts with Proudhon,
a name a sent around.

00:18:02.730 --> 00:18:09.068
Pierre-Joseph Proudhon.
 

00:18:09.068 --> 00:18:13.296
He was from the east of France,
from Besançon,

00:18:13.296 --> 00:18:16.710
in the mountainous
Franche-Comté.

00:18:16.710 --> 00:18:18.630
He believed that if you didn't
have the state,

00:18:18.630 --> 00:18:22.002
the people could live pretty
much as with a little bit of

00:18:22.002 --> 00:18:24.930
prosperity that they had,
a few chickens,

00:18:24.930 --> 00:18:26.259
a little piece of land.
 

00:18:26.259 --> 00:18:29.450
People tended to live like that
there.

00:18:29.450 --> 00:18:32.429
It was a place where nobody had
very much but everybody had

00:18:32.429 --> 00:18:33.559
enough to get along.
 

00:18:33.559 --> 00:18:35.460
He writes the following.
 

00:18:35.460 --> 00:18:40.048
It's in my lecture notes.
 

00:18:40.048 --> 00:18:43.874
To be governed is to be
watched, inspected,

00:18:43.874 --> 00:18:47.104
spied upon, directed,
law-driven, numbered,

00:18:47.104 --> 00:18:48.794
regulated, enrolled,
indoctrinated,

00:18:48.794 --> 00:18:51.009
preached at,
controlled, checked,

00:18:51.009 --> 00:18:53.140
estimated, valued,
censored,

00:18:53.140 --> 00:18:56.713
commanded by creatures who have
neither the right nor the wisdom

00:18:56.713 --> 00:18:58.190
nor the virtue to do so.
 

00:18:58.190 --> 00:19:01.624
To be governed at every
operation at every transaction,

00:19:01.624 --> 00:19:04.000
noted, registered,
counted, taxed,

00:19:04.000 --> 00:19:06.327
stamped, measured,
numbered, assessed,

00:19:06.327 --> 00:19:08.598
licensed, authorized,
admonished, prevented,

00:19:08.598 --> 00:19:11.759
forbidden, reformed,
corrected, punished,

00:19:11.759 --> 00:19:15.104
under the pretext of public
utility in the name of the

00:19:15.104 --> 00:19:18.259
general interest to be placed
under taxes, drilled,

00:19:18.259 --> 00:19:20.647
fleeced,
exploited, monopolized,

00:19:20.647 --> 00:19:24.230
extorted from,
squeezed, poached, and robbed.

00:19:24.230 --> 00:19:27.428
At the slightest resistance or
the first word of complaint to

00:19:27.428 --> 00:19:28.972
be repressed,
fired, vilified,

00:19:28.972 --> 00:19:30.558
harassed,
hunted down,

00:19:30.558 --> 00:19:32.519
abused, clubbed,
disarmed,

00:19:32.519 --> 00:19:34.836
bound, choked,
imprisoned, judged,

00:19:34.836 --> 00:19:36.650
condemned,
shot, deported,

00:19:36.650 --> 00:19:38.390
sacrificed, sold,
betrayed,

00:19:38.390 --> 00:19:40.839
and to crown all,
mocked, ridiculed,

00:19:40.839 --> 00:19:43.630
derided, outraged, dishonored.
 

00:19:43.630 --> 00:19:44.470
That is government.
 

00:19:44.470 --> 00:19:46.109
That is its justice.
 

00:19:46.109 --> 00:19:49.519
That is its morality.
 

00:19:49.519 --> 00:19:54.368
He wrote a pamphlet in 1841
called What is Property?

00:19:54.368 --> 00:19:58.298
His answer is,
"Property is theft."

00:19:58.298 --> 00:20:01.220
He didn't mean that all
property was theft.

00:20:01.220 --> 00:20:03.532
What he meant was too much
property was theft,

00:20:03.532 --> 00:20:05.230
or unearned property was theft.
 

00:20:05.230 --> 00:20:08.500
Proudhon had lots of influence
among some peasants,

00:20:08.500 --> 00:20:09.940
but mostly artisans.
 

00:20:09.940 --> 00:20:13.220
In the world, by the way,
that the great painter,

00:20:13.220 --> 00:20:17.722
Gustave Courbet painted a lot,
in the area around

00:20:17.722 --> 00:20:21.393
Besançon or Nantes,
lots of really marvelous

00:20:21.393 --> 00:20:24.166
paintings of people at work,
the stone breakers and people

00:20:24.166 --> 00:20:26.038
just working their guts out for
very little.

00:20:26.038 --> 00:20:29.748
Proudhon, in 1848,
it's said he went down in Paris

00:20:29.748 --> 00:20:33.001
and put a brick on a barricade
and threw up,

00:20:33.001 --> 00:20:37.240
nauseated by the thought of
violence, of revolution.

00:20:37.240 --> 00:20:41.183
His successors,
sort of the leaders of the

00:20:41.183 --> 00:20:51.430
anarchist movements,
were Mikhail Bakunin,

00:20:51.430 --> 00:20:56.660
an enormously tall, bearded,
heavy-drinking, heavy-eating,

00:20:56.660 --> 00:21:01.744
heavy-sweating Russian noble,
a prince who was an anarchist

00:21:01.744 --> 00:21:03.588
who said,
"The revolution will come.

00:21:03.588 --> 00:21:06.818
It will come with a single
spark and all the hundreds of

00:21:06.818 --> 00:21:09.578
millions of toilers,
the serfs will rise up,

00:21:09.578 --> 00:21:12.588
and they will slay their social
betters,

00:21:12.588 --> 00:21:16.250
and create this new brave world
based upon their village

00:21:16.250 --> 00:21:17.450
harmonies."
 

00:21:17.450 --> 00:21:23.483
He said, "Destruction is a
creative passion,"

00:21:23.483 --> 00:21:26.390
entre guillemets.
 

00:21:26.390 --> 00:21:30.650
Destruction is a creative
passion.

00:21:30.650 --> 00:21:33.390
In 1848 he led police on a
merry chase.

00:21:33.390 --> 00:21:36.608
He spent time in the Russian
slammer.

00:21:36.608 --> 00:21:39.737
He escapes through Japan,
goes through the United States

00:21:39.737 --> 00:21:42.410
and ends up back in London,
terrified people.

00:21:42.410 --> 00:21:45.346
His image, this is before
photographs or photographs are

00:21:45.346 --> 00:21:47.801
just starting out,
and there are photographs of

00:21:47.801 --> 00:21:48.230
him.
 

00:21:48.230 --> 00:21:50.758
He met Marx,
whom he hated,

00:21:50.758 --> 00:21:52.798
and Marx hated him.
 

00:21:52.798 --> 00:21:55.952
He thought that Marx was
ruining class struggle,

00:21:55.952 --> 00:21:59.576
was ruining revolution by
preaching over and over again

00:21:59.576 --> 00:22:01.789
about waiting for revolution.
 

00:22:01.789 --> 00:22:03.068
Class-conscious workers.
 

00:22:03.068 --> 00:22:06.238
What you need is peasants to
rise up as they had in

00:22:06.238 --> 00:22:09.280
Pugachev's rebellion,
and all the other rebellions in

00:22:09.280 --> 00:22:11.538
the early seventeenth and
eighteenth century.

00:22:11.538 --> 00:22:18.500
He dies in the early 1870s,
a phenomenal character.

00:22:18.500 --> 00:22:23.395
The other Russian,
a gentle man,

00:22:23.395 --> 00:22:27.977
a geographer,
Peter Kropotkin,

00:22:27.977 --> 00:22:33.980
K-R-O-P-O-T-K-I-N,
is in the book.

00:22:33.980 --> 00:22:37.279
He wrote a pamphlet called
The Anarchist Morality.

00:22:37.279 --> 00:22:39.358
When you get rid of the state,
people are basically good.

00:22:39.358 --> 00:22:41.009
Anarchists believe that people
are good.

00:22:41.009 --> 00:22:43.410
There's a tradition from
Rousseau, by the way,

00:22:43.410 --> 00:22:44.048
there too.
 

00:22:44.048 --> 00:22:47.125
Rousseau, who lived in the east
of France, or what would become

00:22:47.125 --> 00:22:50.298
France, around Chambéry,
who believed in the primitive.

00:22:50.298 --> 00:22:52.624
Anarchists believe that
primitive social relations and

00:22:52.624 --> 00:22:54.509
even primitive ways of producing
things,

00:22:54.509 --> 00:22:59.569
just associations you enter in
because you want to,

00:22:59.569 --> 00:23:02.750
were the future.
 

00:23:02.750 --> 00:23:06.493
Kropotkin, who at the end of
his life was once toasted by the

00:23:06.493 --> 00:23:09.145
king of England,
and who had turned against the

00:23:09.145 --> 00:23:11.200
Russian Revolution--he died in,
I think,

00:23:11.200 --> 00:23:12.838
1921 or 1922.
 

00:23:12.838 --> 00:23:16.133
He was terrified,
just disgusted by the Russian

00:23:16.133 --> 00:23:20.500
Revolution, which was already
creating a centralized state.

00:23:20.500 --> 00:23:21.500
That's what he hated.
 

00:23:21.500 --> 00:23:22.558
He hated states.
 

00:23:22.558 --> 00:23:24.619
"You must destroy the
state."

00:23:24.619 --> 00:23:26.578
But he was a gentle man.
 

00:23:26.578 --> 00:23:28.869
Yet he and a guy called Paul
Brousse,

00:23:28.869 --> 00:23:31.342
you don't have to remember,
who became a socialist leader

00:23:31.342 --> 00:23:34.390
and then went nuts later--that's
not a very clinical term,

00:23:34.390 --> 00:23:38.786
but he had big problems
later--they create the term

00:23:38.786 --> 00:23:42.039
"propaganda by the
deed."

00:23:42.039 --> 00:23:43.809
What is a deed?
 

00:23:43.809 --> 00:23:46.000
A deed is a bomb.
 

00:23:46.000 --> 00:23:47.880
A deed is an attack.
 

00:23:47.880 --> 00:23:49.318
It's the murder of an official.
 

00:23:49.318 --> 00:23:52.858
The anarchists weren't the only
ones doing this stuff.

00:23:52.858 --> 00:23:55.270
There was a Russian group,
briefly mentioned,

00:23:55.270 --> 00:23:57.902
called Narodnaya Volya,
who believed in kind of a

00:23:57.902 --> 00:24:00.259
hierarchical post-revolutionary
system.

00:24:00.259 --> 00:24:02.558
What they wanted to do was set
out and kill officials.

00:24:02.558 --> 00:24:05.528
But so did the anarchist
terrorists.

00:24:05.528 --> 00:24:09.113
They killed officials,
one of which you've heard of

00:24:09.113 --> 00:24:09.828
already.
 

00:24:09.828 --> 00:24:11.190
You've probably heard of some
of the others.

00:24:11.190 --> 00:24:14.730
President McKinley in 1901,
Buffalo, New York,

00:24:14.730 --> 00:24:18.373
is killed by somebody who
received funds from an anarchist

00:24:18.373 --> 00:24:21.313
organization in Patterson,
New Jersey, I think,

00:24:21.313 --> 00:24:22.720
or is that Bresci?
 

00:24:22.720 --> 00:24:26.409
Anyway, Bresci kills King
Umberto I of Italy,

00:24:26.409 --> 00:24:29.259
another anarchist
assassination.

00:24:29.259 --> 00:24:33.407
They kill five or six leaders
during this period of anarchist

00:24:33.407 --> 00:24:36.519
heyday really,
the late nineteenth century.

00:24:36.519 --> 00:24:41.327
King Umberto I of Italy said
that he considered assassination

00:24:41.327 --> 00:24:43.088
a professional risk.
 

00:24:43.088 --> 00:24:46.633
There were two attempts on his
life and the third one nails

00:24:46.633 --> 00:24:47.000
him.
 

00:24:47.000 --> 00:24:50.117
Alexander II,
who liberated the serfs,

00:24:50.117 --> 00:24:55.007
is killed when he gets out of a
sled to look at a bomb that

00:24:55.007 --> 00:24:56.440
doesn't work.
 

00:24:56.440 --> 00:24:59.223
Elizabeth, the empress of
Austria-Hungary,

00:24:59.223 --> 00:25:03.028
who couldn't stand Franz Joseph
and lived apart from him,

00:25:03.028 --> 00:25:04.930
is assassinated as well.
 

00:25:04.930 --> 00:25:09.130
But most anarchists were not
killers.

00:25:09.130 --> 00:25:11.098
Now, if you think of American
history,

00:25:11.098 --> 00:25:12.589
those of you who had Glenda's
course,

00:25:12.589 --> 00:25:15.049
or David Blight's,
other people here,

00:25:15.049 --> 00:25:17.990
you might know about Haymarket,
the Haymarket affair in the

00:25:17.990 --> 00:25:18.400
1880s.
 

00:25:18.400 --> 00:25:20.584
There they hanged four
anarchists who were called

00:25:20.584 --> 00:25:21.950
les pendus in France.
 

00:25:21.950 --> 00:25:22.930
They had enormous influence.
 

00:25:22.930 --> 00:25:27.061
The les pendus were the
hanged, as they're swinging in

00:25:27.061 --> 00:25:29.680
the breeze in a Chicago prison
yard.

00:25:29.680 --> 00:25:32.894
They were anarchists and they
inspire someone like Emma

00:25:32.894 --> 00:25:35.133
Goldman,
who was a Russian-Jewish

00:25:35.133 --> 00:25:38.792
immigrant to the United States,
who becomes an important

00:25:38.792 --> 00:25:40.029
American anarchist.
 

00:25:40.029 --> 00:25:46.241
Anarchists set off to kill
policemen, or to kill heads of

00:25:46.241 --> 00:25:51.432
state, or to kill generals;
propaganda by the deed,

00:25:51.432 --> 00:25:55.210
the spark that will ignite this
revolution.

00:25:55.210 --> 00:25:59.130
But the man you see before
you--and I have become today a

00:25:59.130 --> 00:26:00.390
very modern man.
 

00:26:00.390 --> 00:26:03.619
I want to tell you,
because this is my first try at

00:26:03.619 --> 00:26:04.460
PowerPoint.
 

00:26:04.460 --> 00:26:08.047
The person that you see before
you is the guy I've been

00:26:08.047 --> 00:26:09.308
following around.
 

00:26:09.308 --> 00:26:12.058
I got interested in him for two
reasons.

00:26:12.058 --> 00:26:17.419
One is that he is the first,
really, along with a bombing at

00:26:17.419 --> 00:26:21.960
an opera in Barcelona,
the Liceo to target ordinary

00:26:21.960 --> 00:26:22.960
people.
 

00:26:22.960 --> 00:26:26.582
To say that people of a social
class were guilty because they

00:26:26.582 --> 00:26:27.848
were who they were.
 

00:26:27.848 --> 00:26:33.430
The spark does not necessarily
have to be lit by killing a head

00:26:33.430 --> 00:26:34.598
of a state.
 

00:26:34.598 --> 00:26:37.453
Sadi Carnot,
who would get his in 1894 on

00:26:37.453 --> 00:26:41.950
the Rue de la République
in Lyon, president of France.

00:26:41.950 --> 00:26:46.680
He takes the decision to kill
ordinary people.

00:26:46.680 --> 00:26:49.058
Lots of terrorists since then
have taken that decision.

00:26:49.058 --> 00:26:57.694
A classic example is insurgents
in Punjab in India in the 1920s,

00:26:57.694 --> 00:27:01.259
bombing officers' clubs.
 

00:27:01.259 --> 00:27:03.568
There's a terrifying scene in
that fantastic,

00:27:03.568 --> 00:27:05.634
but very difficult
movie--because of the torture

00:27:05.634 --> 00:27:07.289
scene,
I can't even use it in the

00:27:07.289 --> 00:27:09.858
French History course--The
Battle of Algiers.

00:27:09.858 --> 00:27:13.038
You are with this woman who's
planting a bomb in a café

00:27:13.038 --> 00:27:15.490
and she sees the people who are
going to die.

00:27:15.490 --> 00:27:18.288
She sees babies with their
mothers.

00:27:18.288 --> 00:27:21.920
She sees people having a drink
in the French community there.

00:27:21.920 --> 00:27:23.990
She takes the decision to place
the bomb.

00:27:23.990 --> 00:27:26.519
I believe that it kind of
started with this guy.

00:27:26.519 --> 00:27:28.509
This is, again,
not somebody I admire.

00:27:28.509 --> 00:27:29.720
I know him.
 

00:27:29.720 --> 00:27:32.368
Everywhere he's lived I've been.
 

00:27:32.368 --> 00:27:35.986
I guess if you're going to
write a book about somebody as a

00:27:35.986 --> 00:27:39.088
prism on something or other,
it's good to pick somebody who

00:27:39.088 --> 00:27:41.990
only lived to be twenty-one,
because it's a shorter book.

00:27:41.990 --> 00:27:46.288
He was guillotined in May 1894.
 

00:27:46.288 --> 00:27:50.390
Again, I do not admire him,
but I'm going to tell you about

00:27:50.390 --> 00:27:51.309
him anyway.
 

00:27:51.309 --> 00:27:54.500
With the help of PowerPoint!
 

