I've got to remember how to do
this.

00:27:57.410 --> 00:27:59.250
All right.
 

00:27:59.250 --> 00:28:00.328
That's Émile Henry.
 

00:28:00.328 --> 00:28:02.738
His father was a
communard who was

00:28:02.738 --> 00:28:05.567
condemned to death,
somebody who'd fought in the

00:28:05.567 --> 00:28:06.289
Commune.
 

00:28:06.289 --> 00:28:09.160
So, this guy is born in Spain.
 

00:28:09.160 --> 00:28:12.951
His father contracted mercury
poisoning in Spain,

00:28:12.951 --> 00:28:17.220
and comes back to France after
the amnesty and dies.

00:28:17.220 --> 00:28:19.779
He has an older brother and a
younger brother.

00:28:19.779 --> 00:28:25.890
What he does is,
on a day in 1894,

00:28:25.890 --> 00:28:32.845
he sets out with a bomb and he
walks in the fancy boulevards

00:28:32.845 --> 00:28:37.255
that, for him,
represent all of the class

00:28:37.255 --> 00:28:41.509
differences between wealthy and
poor people,

00:28:41.509 --> 00:28:43.798
center versus periphery and all
of that.

00:28:43.798 --> 00:28:47.166
He goes down to the Café
Terminus, which is on your

00:28:47.166 --> 00:28:47.640
right.
 

00:28:47.640 --> 00:28:52.118
It's those awnings there near
the Gare Saint-Lazare.

00:28:52.118 --> 00:28:54.960
I've had the rather odd
experience of twice,

00:28:54.960 --> 00:28:57.460
once with friends and once with
my son,

00:28:57.460 --> 00:29:01.710
having eaten in the restaurant
that my book subject blew up,

00:29:01.710 --> 00:29:05.440
because it's still there,
and sitting at the same table.

00:29:05.440 --> 00:29:08.038
He goes to four or five cafes,
but there are not enough

00:29:08.038 --> 00:29:09.288
innocent people in them.
 

00:29:09.288 --> 00:29:13.035
So, he goes to the Terminus
where there is a gypsy orchestra

00:29:13.035 --> 00:29:14.940
playing, pays for two beers.
 

00:29:14.940 --> 00:29:17.593
That seems a little odd,
anarchist paying for a beer,

00:29:17.593 --> 00:29:20.398
because the right to theft was
something that they still

00:29:20.398 --> 00:29:22.390
believed in, many of them,
not all.

00:29:22.390 --> 00:29:24.279
Most were not terrorists,
remember that.

00:29:38.788 --> 00:29:40.160
He goes into the Café
Terminus.

00:29:40.160 --> 00:29:42.109
He gets a cigar.
 

00:29:42.109 --> 00:29:43.000
He lights the fuse.
 

00:29:43.000 --> 00:29:46.250
He throws it toward a
chandelier and it blows up,

00:29:46.250 --> 00:29:49.569
killing one and wounding about
eighteen people.

00:29:49.569 --> 00:29:51.240
That's not him.
 

00:29:51.240 --> 00:29:53.318
This anarchist is called
Malatesta, who doesn't look

00:29:53.318 --> 00:29:54.420
particularly scary there.
 

00:29:54.420 --> 00:30:00.930
Émile Henry had gone
back to the Paris region.

00:30:00.930 --> 00:30:06.470
His mother had a very pitiful
auberge.

00:30:06.470 --> 00:30:09.980
This is the era of bomb attacks
in the early 1890s.

00:30:09.980 --> 00:30:12.980
That's a marmite,
as bombs were sometimes called.

00:30:12.980 --> 00:30:17.200
He became an anarchist.
 

00:30:17.200 --> 00:30:18.960
His brother had already become
an anarchist.

00:30:18.960 --> 00:30:23.140
To put yourself into the early
1890s in Paris,

00:30:23.140 --> 00:30:27.413
ordinary people,
but not so much as the elites,

00:30:27.413 --> 00:30:31.130
were terrified of anarchist
bombers.

00:30:31.130 --> 00:30:34.528
Ravachol, a name I sent around,
who was a poor,

00:30:34.528 --> 00:30:38.518
pathetic in many ways but
extremely poor guy who'd been

00:30:38.518 --> 00:30:41.029
sent out to beg by his mother.
 

00:30:41.029 --> 00:30:42.598
They had almost no money.
 

00:30:42.598 --> 00:30:44.244
They're from a place called
Saint-Chamond,

00:30:44.244 --> 00:30:45.368
near Saint-Étienne.
 

00:30:45.368 --> 00:30:50.868
Ravachol was a counterfeiter
and finally a murderer.

00:30:50.868 --> 00:30:55.347
He suffocates to death a hermit
who had a mini fortune hidden in

00:30:55.347 --> 00:30:58.759
his bizarre cottage near
Saint-Étienne.

00:30:58.759 --> 00:31:01.528
He escapes from the police and
he goes to Paris.

00:31:01.528 --> 00:31:05.704
In 1891 police beat the hell
out of three anarchists in a

00:31:05.704 --> 00:31:08.240
march, a rather one-sided brawl.
 

00:31:08.240 --> 00:31:12.078
Two of them are condemned to
big-time sentences.

00:31:12.078 --> 00:31:17.250
Ravachol decides to go and to
kill the prosecuting attorney.

00:31:17.250 --> 00:31:20.497
He places a bomb,
not knowing where the apartment

00:31:20.497 --> 00:31:22.460
was, and the bomb blows up.
 

00:31:22.460 --> 00:31:26.868
Then he set other bombs, too.
 

00:31:26.868 --> 00:31:29.586
After having done this,
he goes to a restaurant,

00:31:29.586 --> 00:31:32.477
and he eats rather well,
and he engages a waiter in

00:31:32.477 --> 00:31:33.460
conversation.
 

00:31:33.460 --> 00:31:35.990
He tries to convince the waiter
to be an anarchist.

00:31:35.990 --> 00:31:39.104
The waiter sees he has a scar
on his left hand,

00:31:39.104 --> 00:31:40.118
Ravachol did.
 

00:31:40.118 --> 00:31:42.960
Then he stupidly goes back
later and eats in the same

00:31:42.960 --> 00:31:43.670
restaurant.
 

00:31:43.670 --> 00:31:46.784
Instead of bringing the second
course, the waiter brings the

00:31:46.784 --> 00:31:47.259
police.
 

00:31:47.259 --> 00:31:51.319
After a tremendous struggle,
Ravachol is captured,

00:31:51.319 --> 00:31:57.569
put on trial for his life,
and he memorably holds up--how

00:31:57.569 --> 00:32:06.619
do you work this thing?--anyway,
he is guillotined.

00:32:06.619 --> 00:32:08.298
He's really kind of a bastard.
 

00:32:08.298 --> 00:32:10.817
More than that,
and he killed other people too,

00:32:10.817 --> 00:32:11.420
probably.
 

00:32:11.420 --> 00:32:13.259
But he finally is guillotined.
 

00:32:13.259 --> 00:32:17.700
Two things happened,
not only in Paris but in other

00:32:17.700 --> 00:32:18.500
places.
 

00:32:18.500 --> 00:32:21.656
The people of means living in
the fancy quarters are extremely

00:32:21.656 --> 00:32:22.328
frightened.
 

00:32:22.328 --> 00:32:24.598
There are all sorts of death
threats that get sent around.

00:32:24.598 --> 00:32:28.890
Ravachol, to those anarchist
terrorists, he becomes a martyr.

00:32:28.890 --> 00:32:33.880
Look, here his head is framed
by the guillotine.

00:32:33.880 --> 00:32:37.593
Ravachol, who had been betrayed
by an anarchist friend,

00:32:37.593 --> 00:32:39.450
dies at age thirty-three.
 

00:32:39.450 --> 00:32:42.703
Christ died at age
thirty-three,

00:32:42.703 --> 00:32:45.118
betrayed by a friend.
 

00:32:45.118 --> 00:32:48.797
So, he becomes this sort of,
for radical anarchists,

00:32:48.797 --> 00:32:51.970
he becomes a vision of how life
should be.

00:32:51.970 --> 00:32:54.470
There are songs called La
Ravachol.

00:32:54.470 --> 00:32:58.077
There's another one called
The Dynamite Polka,

00:32:58.077 --> 00:32:58.980
being sung.
 

00:32:58.980 --> 00:33:01.981
Dynamite, from the point of
view of anarchists,

00:33:01.981 --> 00:33:03.808
leveled the playing field.
 

00:33:03.808 --> 00:33:08.769
They viewed dynamite rather as
the way in which muskets helped

00:33:08.769 --> 00:33:11.210
end the domain of feudalism.
 

00:33:11.210 --> 00:33:14.108
It levels the playing field.
 

00:33:14.108 --> 00:33:16.259
Dynamite, after all,
was invented by whom?

00:33:16.259 --> 00:33:18.660
By Nobel, as in the Nobel Prize.
 

00:33:18.660 --> 00:33:22.490
So the people who support
dynamite in French are called

00:33:22.490 --> 00:33:25.400
the dynamitards,
the dynamiters.

00:33:25.400 --> 00:33:26.460
The Dynamite Polka.
 

00:33:26.460 --> 00:33:28.282
In Montmartre,
where you have a lot of

00:33:28.282 --> 00:33:29.859
anarchist writers and artists.
 

00:33:29.859 --> 00:33:33.430
Pizarro is an anarchist.
 

00:33:33.430 --> 00:33:36.156
The literary and art critic,
above all art,

00:33:36.156 --> 00:33:38.558
Félix
Fénéon,

00:33:38.558 --> 00:33:40.049
who was a friend of
Émile Henry,

00:33:40.049 --> 00:33:42.880
is an anarchist as well.
 

00:33:42.880 --> 00:33:46.859
So, it's into this world that
the young Émile Henry.

00:33:46.859 --> 00:33:47.400
Here you go.
 

00:33:47.400 --> 00:33:48.058
Here's this one.
 

00:33:48.058 --> 00:33:50.291
I've read hundreds of these
things that said,

00:33:50.291 --> 00:33:52.930
"You've always been hard
with your domestics.

00:33:52.930 --> 00:33:54.420
You're going to be blown up.
 

00:33:54.420 --> 00:33:56.180
Death to the riches."
 

00:33:56.180 --> 00:33:56.920
There are hundreds of these
things.

00:33:56.920 --> 00:33:58.900
They're sent all over Paris,
not just the fancy

00:33:58.900 --> 00:33:59.588
neighborhoods.
 

00:33:59.588 --> 00:34:03.574
There, hundreds and hundreds of
times, at the airports you hear

00:34:03.574 --> 00:34:07.173
these explosions sometimes as
they blow up suitcases that

00:34:07.173 --> 00:34:08.780
haven't been claimed.
 

00:34:08.780 --> 00:34:14.170
That's the first known machine
that blows up suspect items,

00:34:14.170 --> 00:34:16.793
including lots of bad
jokes--sardine cans with a

00:34:16.793 --> 00:34:18.860
little bit of powder left in
them,

00:34:18.860 --> 00:34:20.000
and that kind of thing.
 

00:34:20.000 --> 00:34:24.873
It's in this world that Emile
Henry learns to hate,

00:34:24.873 --> 00:34:27.699
and that he certainly does.
 

00:34:27.699 --> 00:34:30.929
That's where his mom had her
auberge.

00:34:30.929 --> 00:34:34.423
Ironically, it's near Euro
Disney now, but then it was a

00:34:34.423 --> 00:34:35.059
village.
 

00:34:35.059 --> 00:34:35.739
That's not the one.
 

00:34:35.739 --> 00:34:36.940
It was up the street a little
bit.

00:34:36.940 --> 00:34:38.429
I did follow him around,
you can see.

00:34:38.429 --> 00:34:39.889
There's his mother there.
 

00:34:39.889 --> 00:34:43.889
Up on the right is one of the
places he lived,

00:34:43.889 --> 00:34:47.266
always around,
except for one occasion,

00:34:47.266 --> 00:34:48.599
Montmartre.
 

00:34:48.599 --> 00:34:51.250
That's his girlfriend.
 

00:34:51.250 --> 00:34:52.530
He had unrequited love.
 

00:34:52.530 --> 00:34:54.536
She had the disadvantage of
being married to another

00:34:54.536 --> 00:34:55.010
anarchist.
 

00:34:55.010 --> 00:34:56.849
He writes her clumsy poems.
 

00:34:56.849 --> 00:34:57.840
He falls in love with her.
 

00:34:57.840 --> 00:34:59.000
She blows him off.
 

00:34:59.000 --> 00:35:02.030
But in the end,
she wanted to take full credit

00:35:02.030 --> 00:35:05.434
before the press for having been
the lover of Émile Henry

00:35:05.434 --> 00:35:07.110
after his deeds,
his bombs,

00:35:07.110 --> 00:35:08.300
but he wasn't.
 

00:35:08.300 --> 00:35:10.110
That's one of the places he
worked in Paris.

00:35:10.110 --> 00:35:10.739
I love that.
 

00:35:10.739 --> 00:35:13.177
That's a beautiful sign and
that company hasn't existed

00:35:13.177 --> 00:35:14.079
since World War I.
 

00:35:14.079 --> 00:35:16.250
But you can follow him around.
 

00:35:16.250 --> 00:35:20.603
In 1892, Émile Henry,
two years earlier,

00:35:20.603 --> 00:35:22.780
he had killed before.
 

00:35:22.780 --> 00:35:26.554
There was a strike in the south
of France, glassworkers in

00:35:26.554 --> 00:35:27.150
Camaux.
 

00:35:27.150 --> 00:35:31.146
The third block on the left is
number eleven and that's where

00:35:31.146 --> 00:35:32.280
the company is.
 

00:35:32.280 --> 00:35:36.550
They found a bomb there placed
about 11:00 in the morning.

00:35:36.550 --> 00:35:38.070
Right there.
 

00:35:38.070 --> 00:35:39.550
That's not the way it looked
then.

00:35:39.550 --> 00:35:43.489
I've gotten in there twice to
see where he placed the bomb.

00:35:43.489 --> 00:35:45.460
My son gets a little tired.
 

00:35:45.460 --> 00:35:47.244
"Dad, do we have to look
at another one of these

00:35:47.244 --> 00:35:47.760
places?"
 

00:35:47.760 --> 00:35:51.489
They find the bomb and they
carry it down to the police

00:35:51.489 --> 00:35:53.699
station, which is still there.
 

00:35:53.699 --> 00:35:57.172
It was a reversible bomb,
which means when the chemicals

00:35:57.172 --> 00:35:58.500
run together,
boom!

00:35:58.500 --> 00:36:02.708
It kills five people terribly,
five policeman and a secretary

00:36:02.708 --> 00:36:03.619
among them.
 

00:36:03.619 --> 00:36:06.110
Body parts all over the place.
 

00:36:06.110 --> 00:36:08.507
Emile Henry,
that's one of the places he

00:36:08.507 --> 00:36:09.000
lived.
 

00:36:09.000 --> 00:36:12.416
He is eliminated from the list
of suspects because they said he

00:36:12.416 --> 00:36:15.724
could not have gone on the two
errands his boss sent that day

00:36:15.724 --> 00:36:17.929
from near the station of the
north,

00:36:17.929 --> 00:36:19.768
down toward the center of
Paris,

00:36:19.768 --> 00:36:22.260
then up toward the Arc de
Triomphe,

00:36:22.260 --> 00:36:24.980
gone back to Montmartre and
gotten the bomb,

00:36:24.980 --> 00:36:27.034
placed the bomb,
and gotten back in two hours

00:36:27.034 --> 00:36:27.849
and fifteen minutes.
 

00:36:27.849 --> 00:36:31.780
When he went on trial for his
life in 1894,

00:36:31.780 --> 00:36:34.684
a detective said, "Yes,
he could have done that in two

00:36:34.684 --> 00:36:35.659
hours and fifteen minutes."
 

00:36:35.659 --> 00:36:38.440
So, being a bit of an
empiricist, I did it.

00:36:38.440 --> 00:36:42.726
And I replaced tramway and
Omnibus with a bus and with a

00:36:42.726 --> 00:36:43.349
Metro.
 

00:36:43.349 --> 00:36:46.239
I never take cabs, but I took,
instead of a carriage--of

00:36:46.239 --> 00:36:48.637
course I didn't take that--I
took a cab and I subtracted

00:36:48.637 --> 00:36:51.166
eleven minutes when my cab
couldn't turn left on the Avenue

00:36:51.166 --> 00:36:52.170
de l'Opéra.
 

00:36:52.170 --> 00:36:54.940
He did it.
 

00:36:54.940 --> 00:36:55.889
There's no question about it.
 

00:36:55.889 --> 00:36:58.452
In fact, when they did the
reconstitution of this building,

00:36:58.452 --> 00:37:00.440
he knew every single part of
this building.

00:37:00.440 --> 00:37:01.150
He did it.
 

00:37:01.150 --> 00:37:02.610
There's no question about it.
 

00:37:02.610 --> 00:37:03.940
Why did he hate so?
 

00:37:03.940 --> 00:37:06.619
Part of it again,
this is the theme we've talked

00:37:06.619 --> 00:37:08.898
about before,
was the social geography of

00:37:08.898 --> 00:37:09.469
Paris.
 

00:37:09.469 --> 00:37:12.335
Everywhere he lived,
with one exception that you

00:37:12.335 --> 00:37:14.409
just saw, was in people's Paris.
 

00:37:14.409 --> 00:37:16.210
All of the facades are still
there.

00:37:16.210 --> 00:37:19.293
That's where he lived on the
Rue Véron,

00:37:19.293 --> 00:37:20.940
on the very top floor.
 

00:37:20.940 --> 00:37:22.050
That's where the poor lived.
 

00:37:22.050 --> 00:37:23.880
He gets the bomb there in 1892.
 

00:37:23.880 --> 00:37:27.980
They hated Sacré-Coeur,
for reasons you already know.

00:37:27.980 --> 00:37:32.230
It was a symbol of penance for
the Franco-Prussian War and

00:37:32.230 --> 00:37:34.170
penance for the commune.
 

00:37:34.170 --> 00:37:37.039
His father was one of the
people condemned to death,

00:37:37.039 --> 00:37:40.079
who was lucky enough to get out
and not be executed.

00:37:40.079 --> 00:37:43.344
In a Zola novel that's very
underappreciated called

00:37:43.344 --> 00:37:45.659
Paris,
published in 1898,

00:37:45.659 --> 00:37:49.409
it's about a priest who,
to take an REM song,

00:37:49.409 --> 00:37:51.130
is "losing his
religion."

00:37:51.130 --> 00:37:54.268
His brother is an anarchist,
Guillaume.

00:37:54.268 --> 00:37:57.139
He has fantasies about blowing
this place up.

00:37:57.139 --> 00:37:59.659
I think it's ugly as hell.
 

00:37:59.659 --> 00:38:03.070
I once went with my wife to see
where they cast the huge bell

00:38:03.070 --> 00:38:06.880
that would drive people nuts and
still does, called la Savoyarde.

00:38:06.880 --> 00:38:07.969
But that bell wasn't there.
 

00:38:07.969 --> 00:38:10.141
But as a symbol,
you can't walk around

00:38:10.141 --> 00:38:12.960
Montmartre and not see it from
various places.

00:38:12.960 --> 00:38:17.034
He becomes a terrorist because
the people that he sees around

00:38:17.034 --> 00:38:18.869
him are very,
very poor,

00:38:18.869 --> 00:38:20.811
and he convinces himself,
even though he's an

00:38:20.811 --> 00:38:22.590
intellectual,
he's a bourgeois.

00:38:22.590 --> 00:38:26.474
He could have gotten into the
École Polytechnique,

00:38:26.474 --> 00:38:29.250
which is a super,
Grande École.

00:38:29.250 --> 00:38:30.659
It's a big engineering school.
 

00:38:30.659 --> 00:38:31.800
He's a great student.
 

00:38:31.800 --> 00:38:32.900
He's an intellectual.
 

00:38:32.900 --> 00:38:33.510
That's the other thing.
 

00:38:33.510 --> 00:38:36.710
Besides picking "innocent
people."

00:38:36.710 --> 00:38:38.550
All people are innocent,
but you know what I mean.

00:38:38.550 --> 00:38:43.322
The other thing is he is not a
sad sack or a dangerous one like

00:38:43.322 --> 00:38:44.170
Ravachol.
 

00:38:44.170 --> 00:38:46.570
He is not a guy called
Vaillant,

00:38:46.570 --> 00:38:49.405
who places a little,
teeny tack bomb and throws it

00:38:49.405 --> 00:38:52.539
in the Chamber of Deputies to
call attention to the plight of

00:38:52.539 --> 00:38:54.280
the poor,
and is guillotined.

00:38:54.280 --> 00:38:56.635
The first person in the
nineteenth century guillotined

00:38:56.635 --> 00:38:57.880
who did not kill somebody.
 

00:38:57.880 --> 00:39:00.980
This guy goes out to kill.
 

00:39:00.980 --> 00:39:05.338
There's a scene in an old
Balzac novel called--all Balzac

00:39:05.338 --> 00:39:09.684
novels by definition are old,
obviously--Old Goriot,

00:39:09.684 --> 00:39:13.559
Père Goriot,
in which Rastignac,

00:39:13.559 --> 00:39:16.304
who was sort of this
down-and-out noble who wants to

00:39:16.304 --> 00:39:19.318
make the big time in Paris by
sleeping with all the right

00:39:19.318 --> 00:39:19.909
people.
 

00:39:19.909 --> 00:39:23.114
After Goriot dies,
he's up in the northeast

00:39:23.114 --> 00:39:27.159
quadrant of Paris at Père
Lachaise cemetery.

00:39:27.159 --> 00:39:30.623
He waves his hand down toward
the fancy quarters,

00:39:30.623 --> 00:39:34.880
down ironically near where
Café Terminus would be.

00:39:34.880 --> 00:39:37.188
The fancy quarters,
even before there are

00:39:37.188 --> 00:39:38.860
boulevards,
and he says the equivalent of,

00:39:38.860 --> 00:39:40.840
"It's war between you and
me now, baby."

00:39:40.840 --> 00:39:43.590
That's a rough translation,
but that's what he said.

00:39:43.590 --> 00:39:46.748
Émile Henry,
walking around on the hills and

00:39:46.748 --> 00:39:49.309
seeing people walk down to be
domestics,

00:39:49.309 --> 00:39:52.409
because they couldn't afford to
take the tramway or the Omnibus,

00:39:52.409 --> 00:39:54.039
horse-drawn carriages.
 

00:39:54.039 --> 00:39:57.702
He waves his hand and says,
"It's war between you and

00:39:57.702 --> 00:40:00.396
me, baby,
and I will ignite the spark

00:40:00.396 --> 00:40:03.449
that kills you MFs right
away."

00:40:03.449 --> 00:40:04.719
That's what he does.
 

00:40:04.719 --> 00:40:06.500
When he walked out of his
apartment,

00:40:06.500 --> 00:40:11.003
he looked down and happily he
didn't have to see the Tour

00:40:11.003 --> 00:40:13.992
Montparnasse,
which hadn't been built after

00:40:13.992 --> 00:40:15.929
huge payoffs in the early 1970s.
 

00:40:15.929 --> 00:40:17.590
Disgusting!
 

00:40:17.590 --> 00:40:20.842
But what he could see were
these symbols of capitalism,

00:40:20.842 --> 00:40:22.530
the state, and the church.
 

00:40:22.530 --> 00:40:23.460
What did he see?
 

00:40:23.460 --> 00:40:26.597
He saw the Eiffel Tower,
which was five years old,

00:40:26.597 --> 00:40:29.990
a symbol of the republic and
the bourgeois revolution,

00:40:29.990 --> 00:40:31.079
as he saw it.
 

00:40:31.079 --> 00:40:33.791
He sees the Pantheon,
where they buried all these

00:40:33.791 --> 00:40:36.728
Napoleonic marshals who
basically got a lot of people

00:40:36.728 --> 00:40:39.440
killed if they didn't get
themselves killed.

00:40:39.440 --> 00:40:42.550
And he sees Notre Dame.
 

00:40:42.550 --> 00:40:44.639
He says, "It's war between
you and me."

00:40:44.639 --> 00:40:46.199
This is the façade.
 

00:40:46.199 --> 00:40:47.159
I love this stuff.
 

00:40:47.159 --> 00:40:52.659
The inside building where he
lived isn't there anymore.

00:40:52.659 --> 00:40:55.269
Now it's kind of an area that's
a little bit sketchy.

00:40:55.269 --> 00:40:56.610
There's a lot of drug dealing.
 

00:40:56.610 --> 00:40:58.822
When I got myself into there,
I had to kind of--;I didn't

00:40:58.822 --> 00:41:00.599
want to look like a plainclothes
policeman.

00:41:00.599 --> 00:41:02.949
Do I risk looking like a
plainclothes policeman?

00:41:02.949 --> 00:41:03.699
No.
 

00:41:03.699 --> 00:41:07.518
I didn't want to look like a
tourist sort of slumming.

00:41:07.518 --> 00:41:09.090
I don't look like that much,
either.

00:41:09.090 --> 00:41:11.094
When I went by these guys who
were sort of hanging out there,

00:41:11.094 --> 00:41:12.027
I said,
"Salut les

00:41:12.027 --> 00:41:13.088
gars,"
or "Hi guys,

00:41:13.088 --> 00:41:13.719
what's up?"
 

00:41:13.719 --> 00:41:16.599
I got myself in there to see
where he once had lived.

00:41:16.599 --> 00:41:20.139
The point of that is that you
can see what he saw.

00:41:20.139 --> 00:41:24.023
That gate is exactly the same
as that day when he walked out

00:41:24.023 --> 00:41:26.000
to kill for the second time.
 

00:41:26.000 --> 00:41:31.635
His bomb that he threw into the
Terminus--this is back in 1894,

00:41:31.635 --> 00:41:34.090
this is where we started.
 

00:41:34.090 --> 00:41:37.309
It hit a chandelier and
exploded.

00:41:37.309 --> 00:41:40.260
He said at his trial that he
threw it too low.

00:41:40.260 --> 00:41:42.693
He should have thrown it higher;
it would have killed more

00:41:42.693 --> 00:41:42.980
people.
 

00:41:42.980 --> 00:41:44.280
Only one died.
 

00:41:44.280 --> 00:41:46.019
He'd already killed five before.
 

00:41:46.019 --> 00:41:47.960
People are terrified.
 

00:41:47.960 --> 00:41:49.050
They run all over the place.
 

00:41:49.050 --> 00:41:53.880
It was speculated that his was
sort of an indirect suicide,

00:41:53.880 --> 00:41:57.530
because his unrequited love,
this lady who lived in the

00:41:57.530 --> 00:42:02.909
Boulevard Voltaire,
whose name was Elisa.

00:42:02.909 --> 00:42:06.199
But no, because he tries to
escape in order to kill again.

00:42:06.199 --> 00:42:08.010
They chase him and they catch
him.

00:42:08.010 --> 00:42:09.389
A barber helps catch him.
 

00:42:09.389 --> 00:42:13.271
A controller on the tramway
hits him with the control

00:42:13.271 --> 00:42:17.125
mechanism that punches tickets,
just like in the old days on

00:42:17.125 --> 00:42:18.815
those things,
not that I ever was in a

00:42:18.815 --> 00:42:19.719
horse-drawn carriage.
 

00:42:19.719 --> 00:42:22.039
They get him and they take him.
 

00:42:22.039 --> 00:42:26.532
He's arrested for murder,
Émile Henry,

00:42:26.532 --> 00:42:28.780
and is put on trial.
 

00:42:28.780 --> 00:42:31.360
That's where he's writing his
mother.

00:42:31.360 --> 00:42:34.282
We know a lot about him,
because they kept all these

00:42:34.282 --> 00:42:34.969
documents.
 

00:42:34.969 --> 00:42:37.139
It was so fun doing this.
 

00:42:37.139 --> 00:42:38.110
I love stuff like that.
 

00:42:38.110 --> 00:42:42.429
His mother was devastated,
as you can well imagine.

00:42:42.429 --> 00:42:44.958
She cannot believe that her
Émile could have done

00:42:44.958 --> 00:42:45.280
this.
 

00:42:45.280 --> 00:42:50.139
He was her pride and joy after
the death of the father.

00:42:50.139 --> 00:42:53.360
Those of you who have been to
Paris will recognize this.

00:42:53.360 --> 00:42:54.719
This is the Conciergerie.
 

00:42:54.719 --> 00:42:58.889
This is where Louis XVI,
Danton, Robespierre,

00:42:58.889 --> 00:43:01.199
Marie Antoinette,
and others awaited,

00:43:01.199 --> 00:43:03.760
they put their head between the
little window,

00:43:03.760 --> 00:43:05.403
as they used to say,
la petite

00:43:05.403 --> 00:43:07.518
fenêtre, to be
guillotined.

00:43:07.518 --> 00:43:10.905
It's also got one of the three
most magnificent gothic halls

00:43:10.905 --> 00:43:12.110
anywhere in France.
 

00:43:12.110 --> 00:43:16.322
His guards took notes every
single day about what he said

00:43:16.322 --> 00:43:18.280
and the anarchist songs.
 

00:43:18.280 --> 00:43:22.835
They want to prove that
somebody else was involved in

00:43:22.835 --> 00:43:23.449
this.
 

00:43:23.449 --> 00:43:26.432
There probably was somebody
else in the 1892 attack who

00:43:26.432 --> 00:43:27.980
helped him close the bomb.
 

00:43:27.980 --> 00:43:35.820
So, Emile Henry goes on trial
in April of 1894.

00:43:35.820 --> 00:43:40.534
He makes the famous declaration
in which he says,

00:43:40.534 --> 00:43:44.364
"You have hung us in
Chicago,"

00:43:44.364 --> 00:43:47.019
Haymarket;
"You have garroted

00:43:47.019 --> 00:43:49.079
us," that's slowly
strangling us,

00:43:49.079 --> 00:43:50.639
"in Barcelona."
 

00:43:50.639 --> 00:43:55.092
When Franco was croaking in
1975, they were garroting an

00:43:55.092 --> 00:43:59.059
anarchist even at that time,
1975 in Barcelona.

00:43:59.059 --> 00:44:00.809
"You have shot us in
Germany."

00:44:00.809 --> 00:44:02.498
I don't know how they killed
them in Italy,

00:44:02.498 --> 00:44:04.309
but, "You've killed us in
Italy."

00:44:04.309 --> 00:44:06.860
He says, "You,
the bourgeois,

00:44:06.860 --> 00:44:10.880
who are in this café,
you are not innocent.

00:44:10.880 --> 00:44:13.139
It's because of you,
the petty bourgeois.

00:44:13.139 --> 00:44:14.744
You support les
gros,"

00:44:14.744 --> 00:44:16.496
the big ones,
"on every possible

00:44:16.496 --> 00:44:17.130
occasion.
 

00:44:17.130 --> 00:44:21.670
You forget about us when your
factory owners throw us out when

00:44:21.670 --> 00:44:24.349
we can no longer work any
longer,

00:44:24.349 --> 00:44:27.900
or women workers happy not to
have had to prostitute

00:44:27.900 --> 00:44:32.358
themselves in order to pay their
rent and their husbands' rent by

00:44:32.358 --> 00:44:34.099
the end of the month.
 

00:44:34.099 --> 00:44:36.659
But what you can never do is
destroy anarchism.

00:44:36.659 --> 00:44:39.679
Its roots are too deep."
 

00:44:39.679 --> 00:44:43.572
On the 22^(nd) of May
1894--that's what I said about

00:44:43.572 --> 00:44:48.152
writing a book about somebody
that doesn't live very long--he

00:44:48.152 --> 00:44:51.891
is executed at Place Roquette in
Paris, which was,

00:44:51.891 --> 00:44:55.800
by intent,
the place where the state meted

00:44:55.800 --> 00:44:58.235
out justice,
right in the heart of

00:44:58.235 --> 00:44:59.489
working-class Paris.
 

00:44:59.489 --> 00:45:02.518
That was not an idle selection
of a space.

00:45:02.518 --> 00:45:07.909
We have his notes up to the
very end of his life.

00:45:07.909 --> 00:45:10.750
This guy, Deibler,
is the executioner.

00:45:10.750 --> 00:45:14.280
Monsieur de Paris.
 

00:45:14.280 --> 00:45:18.369
This is the executioner meting
out, in quotes,

00:45:18.369 --> 00:45:20.369
"justice."
 

00:45:20.369 --> 00:45:23.288
Public execution,
by the way, in France,

00:45:23.288 --> 00:45:27.478
maybe I said this already,
was in 1936 at Versailles--the

00:45:27.478 --> 00:45:29.800
last execution was in 1974.
 

00:45:29.800 --> 00:45:32.940
I'm constantly asked by people
all sorts of political opinions

00:45:32.940 --> 00:45:35.559
in France,
where executions,

00:45:35.559 --> 00:45:38.940
public capital punishment is
repudiated by most everybody,

00:45:38.940 --> 00:45:40.380
how that we still have it here.
 

00:45:40.380 --> 00:45:42.545
This is not a political
diatribe, so I won't say

00:45:42.545 --> 00:45:43.559
anything about that.
 

00:45:43.559 --> 00:45:47.016
Anyway, Deibler,
his son was the last public

00:45:47.016 --> 00:45:51.440
executioner, did the last public
execution back when.

00:45:51.440 --> 00:45:53.610
There he is.
 

00:45:53.610 --> 00:45:56.742
There's somebody else putting
their head through the little

00:45:56.742 --> 00:45:57.230
window.
 

00:45:57.230 --> 00:45:59.289
That's what I mean by that.
 

00:46:03.949 --> 00:46:06.179
That's the equivalent of his
mug shot.

00:46:06.179 --> 00:46:13.331
So, he was wrong about the
roots of anarchism being too

00:46:13.331 --> 00:46:14.260
deep.
 

00:46:14.260 --> 00:46:18.070
What clearly happens is that
there was a trial during that

00:46:18.070 --> 00:46:22.148
same summer where they put a lot
of intellectuals on trial who

00:46:22.148 --> 00:46:25.891
did nothing except to say that
they were anarchists or to

00:46:25.891 --> 00:46:27.630
criticize the state.
 

00:46:27.630 --> 00:46:30.108
What my book--it's really a
book also about state

00:46:30.108 --> 00:46:30.780
terrorists.
 

00:46:30.780 --> 00:46:34.679
It's about the overreaction of
states.

00:46:34.679 --> 00:46:36.360
Our state is a good example of
that,

00:46:36.360 --> 00:46:39.659
and the tendency to try to
denigrate anyone who doesn't

00:46:39.659 --> 00:46:41.920
agree with us as being
terrorists,

00:46:41.920 --> 00:46:43.690
whether they were or not.
 

00:46:43.690 --> 00:46:47.269
The intellectuals,
the jury sees through it in

00:46:47.269 --> 00:46:51.963
1894 and only a couple thieves
are condemned and them not to

00:46:51.963 --> 00:46:52.760
death.
 

00:46:52.760 --> 00:46:57.360
There's anarchists in 1968 in
Paris.

00:46:57.360 --> 00:47:00.969
There's a band of anarchists in
about 1909,1910,

00:47:00.969 --> 00:47:04.657
1911, that hold up stores with
most modern tools,

00:47:04.657 --> 00:47:07.269
shotguns and things like that.
 

00:47:07.269 --> 00:47:09.889
The anarchist attacks were over.
 

00:47:09.889 --> 00:47:10.900
There was no question about
that.

00:47:10.900 --> 00:47:12.760
That doesn't make Émile
Henry less interesting.

00:47:12.760 --> 00:47:15.724
As an intellectual,
the cross-class kind of--you

00:47:15.724 --> 00:47:18.500
see this in Middle-Eastern
terrorism, too.

00:47:18.500 --> 00:47:21.539
My book is also about state
terrorists.

00:47:21.539 --> 00:47:26.373
What stops anarchist attacks in
Spain is the fact that the

00:47:26.373 --> 00:47:31.460
public becomes aware that the
police were hideously torturing

00:47:31.460 --> 00:47:36.550
people who did not agree with
the politics of the State.

00:47:36.550 --> 00:47:37.550
They were torturing them.
 

00:47:37.550 --> 00:47:41.077
You see where one could go in a
political diatribe,

00:47:41.077 --> 00:47:42.420
which this isn't.
 

00:47:42.420 --> 00:47:47.726
In Italy when the state
overreacts, anarchist attacks

00:47:47.726 --> 00:47:49.360
virtually end.
 

00:47:49.360 --> 00:47:51.679
Now, anarchism does not end in
Spain.

00:47:51.679 --> 00:47:54.425
It does not end also for
reasons that are perfectly clear

00:47:54.425 --> 00:47:55.699
already in Buenos Aires.
 

00:47:55.699 --> 00:47:59.208
There's still a huge anarchist
community of exiles from these

00:47:59.208 --> 00:48:02.657
Western European countries from
all over the place living in

00:48:02.657 --> 00:48:04.932
London,
ironically in one of the more

00:48:04.932 --> 00:48:07.699
chi-chi parts of London which
was then very poor,

00:48:07.699 --> 00:48:09.952
around Charlotte Street,
where you can't afford to have

00:48:09.952 --> 00:48:10.900
a pint of beer anymore.
 

00:48:10.900 --> 00:48:12.769
That's where they live.
 

00:48:12.769 --> 00:48:14.730
So, he was wrong about that.
 

00:48:14.730 --> 00:48:17.670
The roots of anarchism were too
great.

00:48:17.670 --> 00:48:20.289
But the connection that I want
to make, obviously,

00:48:20.289 --> 00:48:22.628
especially since this is being
filmed it's not the place to do

00:48:22.628 --> 00:48:23.699
it,
but when states,

00:48:23.699 --> 00:48:28.750
including our own, overreact,
what they tend to do is to lash

00:48:28.750 --> 00:48:31.545
out in ways,
and imprison unjustly,

00:48:31.545 --> 00:48:33.610
and torture,
and don't give legal rights.

00:48:33.610 --> 00:48:38.302
What they do is tend to
increase the number of those

00:48:38.302 --> 00:48:40.510
people who despise us.
 

00:48:40.510 --> 00:48:43.208
If you look back,
and again the commune is not a

00:48:43.208 --> 00:48:46.193
bad way of thinking about this,
somebody figured out that of

00:48:46.193 --> 00:48:48.650
all the victims of terrorist
attacks,

00:48:48.650 --> 00:48:52.021
no matter how you define them,
the ratio between victims of

00:48:52.021 --> 00:48:55.525
overreaction by states to
victims of anarchist terror--and

00:48:55.525 --> 00:48:58.230
I'm not apologizing for
anarchist terror.

00:48:58.230 --> 00:48:58.960
I hate it.
 

00:48:58.960 --> 00:49:01.289
I'm not apologizing for terror
of any kind.

00:49:01.289 --> 00:49:02.389
I hate it.
 

00:49:02.389 --> 00:49:05.699
But the ratio was 260:1.
 

00:49:05.699 --> 00:49:09.340
I suppose there's a lesson to
be learned there somewhere.

00:49:09.340 --> 00:49:13.059
But it was fun to follow Emile
Henry around,

00:49:13.059 --> 00:49:17.106
even though I don't admire him,
and to try to give you a sense

00:49:17.106 --> 00:49:21.559
of how people felt when they
hated in the 1890s.

00:49:21.559 --> 00:49:25.429
Their answer was not the same
answer as socialists,

00:49:25.429 --> 00:49:28.989
which are to take power mostly
through electoral processes,

00:49:28.989 --> 00:49:32.289
but to smash the state by
blowing it up.

00:49:32.289 --> 00:49:33.679
See you on Monday.
 

